[src:python-dotenv/configuration-file] A **configuration file**, also known as **config file**, is a file that stores data used to configure a software system such as an application, a server or an operating system.
[src:python-dotenv/configuration-file] Some applications provide a tool to create, modify, and verify the syntax of their configuration files – sometimes via graphical user interface (GUI).
[src:python-dotenv/configuration-file] For context, system administrators may be expected to create and modify text config files via a text editor.
[src:python-dotenv/configuration-file] For server processes and operating-system settings, there is often no standard tool, but operating systems may provide graphical interfaces such as YaST or debconf.
[src:python-dotenv/configuration-file] Some computer programs only read their configuration files at startup.
[src:python-dotenv/configuration-file] Others periodically check the configuration files for changes.
[src:python-dotenv/configuration-file] Users can instruct some programs to re-read the configuration files and apply the changes to the current process, or indeed to read arbitrary files as a configuration file.
[src:python-dotenv/configuration-file] There are no definitive standards or strong conventions.
[src:python-dotenv/configuration-file] In general, a config file can have any format.
[src:python-dotenv/configuration-file] The format that applies to a particular system is determined by the design of that system.
[src:python-dotenv/configuration-file] Often, a standardized format is used since it allows for using tools designed for the format even if not designed for the consuming system.
[src:python-dotenv/configuration-file] In particular, general-purpose serialization formats, such as JSON, XML, and YAML, are often used in open-source and platform-neutral software.
[src:python-dotenv/configuration-file] The specifications for these formats are generally publicly available to support wide-spread use.
[src:python-dotenv/configuration-file] The following table compares notable formats used for configuration data.
[src:python-dotenv/configuration-file] The *syntax typing* column indicates whether the syntax supports data types.
[src:python-dotenv/configuration-file] A format has syntax-typing if a value's type is specified by syntax – e.g.
[src:python-dotenv/configuration-file] `true` is a Boolean while `"true"` is a string.
[src:python-dotenv/configuration-file] A format does not have syntax-typing if a value's type is based on semantics – e.g.
[src:python-dotenv/configuration-file] `true` and `"true"` are both Boolean if the parser expects a Boolean.
[src:python-dotenv/configuration-file] Opinions on the value of syntax-typing vary.
[src:python-dotenv/configuration-file] The following are examples of config files organized by the operating systems on which they are commonly used.
[src:python-dotenv/configuration-file] Many different file formats are used on Unix and Unix-like operating systems.
[src:python-dotenv/configuration-file] Even so, there is a strong tradition of using human-editable, plain text formats including simple key–value pair.
[src:python-dotenv/configuration-file] Filename extensions of `.cnf`, `.conf`, `.cfg`, `.cf` or `.ini` are often used.
[src:python-dotenv/configuration-file] Many formats allow comments, in which case, individual settings can be disabled by prepending with the comment character.
[src:python-dotenv/configuration-file] Often the default configuration files contain extensive internal documentation in the form of comments and man files are also typically used to document the format and options available.
[src:python-dotenv/configuration-file] System-wide software often uses configuration files stored in `/etc`, while user applications often use a "dotfile" – a file or directory in the home directory prefixed with a period, which in Unix hides the file or directory from casual listing.
[src:python-dotenv/configuration-file] Since this causes pollution, newer user applications generally make their own folder in the `.config` directory, a standardized subdirectory of the home directory.
[src:python-dotenv/configuration-file] Similar to config files, a run command (rc) shell script can configure a shell session.
[src:python-dotenv/configuration-file] Often, such scripts are named with an `rc` suffix after the consuming program's name such as `.xinitrc`, `.vimrc`, `.bashrc`, `xsane.rc`.
[src:python-dotenv/configuration-file] By contrast, IBM's AIX uses an Object Data Manager (ODM) database to store much of its system settings.
[src:python-dotenv/configuration-file] MS-DOS primarily relied on the `CONFIG.SYS` config file, a plain text file with simple key–value pairs (e.g.
[src:python-dotenv/configuration-file] MS-DOS 6 introduced the INI-file format.
[src:python-dotenv/configuration-file] Similar to an rc file, the batch file named `AUTOEXEC.BAT` ran commands on startup.
[src:python-dotenv/configuration-file] Both these files were retained up to Windows 98SE, which still ran on top of MS-DOS.
[src:python-dotenv/configuration-file] DOS applications used a wide variety of individual configuration files, most of them binary, proprietary and undocumented - and there were no common conventions or formats.
[src:python-dotenv/configuration-file] Early Windows operating systems heavily utilized plain-text INI files which served as the primary mechanism to configure the operating system and applications.
[src:python-dotenv/configuration-file] The APIs to read and write from these still exist in Windows, but after 1993, Microsoft began to steer developers away from using INI files and toward storing settings in the registry, a hierarchical database to store configuration settings, which was introduced with Windows NT.
[src:python-dotenv/configuration-file] Later systems use XML and other formats instead of the registry.
[src:python-dotenv/configuration-file] The Property List is the standard configuration file format in macOS (as well as in iOS, NeXTSTEP, GNUstep and Cocoa applications).
[src:python-dotenv/configuration-file] It uses the filename extension `.plist`.
[src:python-dotenv/configuration-file] IBM's OS/2 uses a binary format, also with a .INI suffix, but this differs from the Windows versions.
[src:python-dotenv/configuration-file] It contains a list of lists of untyped key–value pairs.
[src:python-dotenv/configuration-file] Two files control system-wide settings: OS2.INI and OS2SYS.INI.
[src:python-dotenv/configuration-file] Application developers can choose whether to use them or to create a specific file for their applications.
[src:python-dotenv/configuration-file] HarmonyOS and OpenHarmony-based operating systems use JSON config files, named `config.json`.
[src:python-dotenv/configuration-file] The platform IDE, DevEco Studio, provides methods for editing `config.json`.
[src:python-dotenv/configuration-management] CM applied over the lifecycle of a system provides visibility and control of its performance, functional, and physical attributes.
[src:python-dotenv/configuration-management] CM verifies that a system performs as intended, and is documented in sufficient detail to support its projected life cycle.
[src:python-dotenv/configuration-management] The CM process facilitates orderly management of system information and system changes for purposes such as to revise capability; improve performance, reliability, or maintainability; extend life; reduce costs; reduce risk and liability; or correct defects.
[src:python-dotenv/configuration-management] The relatively minimal cost of implementing CM is returned manyfold in cost avoidance.
[src:python-dotenv/configuration-management] The lack of CM (or its ineffectual implementation) can be very expensive and sometimes can have such catastrophic consequences such as failure of equipment or loss of life.
[src:python-dotenv/configuration-management] CM emphasizes the functional relation between parts, subsystems, and systems for effectively controlling system change.
[src:python-dotenv/configuration-management] It helps to verify that proposed changes are systematically considered to minimize adverse effects.
[src:python-dotenv/configuration-management] Changes to the system are proposed, evaluated, and implemented using a standardized, systematic approach that ensures consistency, and proposed changes are evaluated in terms of their anticipated impact on the entire system.
[src:python-dotenv/configuration-management] CM verifies that changes are carried out as specified and that documentation of items and systems reflects their true configuration.
[src:python-dotenv/configuration-management] A complete CM program includes provisions for the storing, tracking, and updating of all system information on a component, subsystem, and system basis.
[src:python-dotenv/configuration-management] A structured CM program ensures that documentation (e.g., requirements, design, test, and acceptance documentation) for items is accurate and consistent with the actual physical design of the item.
[src:python-dotenv/configuration-management] In many cases, without CM, the documentation exists but is not consistent with the item itself.
[src:python-dotenv/configuration-management] For this reason, engineers, contractors, and management are frequently forced to develop documentation reflecting the actual status of the item before they can proceed with a change.
[src:python-dotenv/configuration-management] This reverse engineering process is wasteful in terms of human and other resources and can be minimized or eliminated using CM.
[src:python-dotenv/configuration-management] Configuration management originated in the United States Department of Defense in the 1950s as a technical management discipline for hardware material items—and it is now a standard practice in virtually every industry.
[src:python-dotenv/configuration-management] The CM process became its own technical discipline in the late 1960s when the DoD developed a series of military standards called the "480 series" (i.e., MIL-STD-480, MIL-STD-481 and MIL-STD-483) that were subsequently issued in the 1970s.
[src:python-dotenv/configuration-management] This marked the beginning of what has now evolved into the most widely distributed and accepted standard on CM, ANSI–EIA–649–1998.
[src:python-dotenv/configuration-management] Many of these functions and models have redefined CM from its traditional holistic approach to technical management.
[src:python-dotenv/configuration-management] Some treat CM as being similar to a librarian activity and break out change control or change management as a separate or standalone discipline.
[src:python-dotenv/configuration-management] CM is the practice of handling changes systematically so that a system maintains its integrity over time.
[src:python-dotenv/configuration-management] CM implements the policies, procedures, techniques, and tools that manage, evaluate proposed changes, track change status, and maintain an inventory of system and support documents as the system changes.
[src:python-dotenv/configuration-management] CM programs and plans provide technical and administrative direction to the development and implementation of the procedures, functions, services, tools, processes, and resources required to successfully develop and support a complex system.
[src:python-dotenv/configuration-management] During system development, CM allows program management to track requirements throughout the life-cycle through acceptance and operations and maintenance.
[src:python-dotenv/configuration-management] As changes inevitably occur in the requirements and design, they must be approved and documented, creating an accurate record of the system status.
[src:python-dotenv/configuration-management] Ideally the CM process is applied throughout the system life cycle.
[src:python-dotenv/configuration-management] Many professionals mix up or get confused with Asset management (AM, see also ISO/IEC 19770), where it inventories the assets on hand.
[src:python-dotenv/configuration-management] The key difference between CM and AM is that the former does not manage the financial accounting aspect but the service that the system supports or in other words, that the latter (AM) is trying to realize value from an IT asset.
[src:python-dotenv/configuration-management] The CM process for both hardware and software configuration items comprises five distinct disciplines as established in the MIL–HDBK–61A and in ANSI/EIA-649.
[src:python-dotenv/configuration-management] Members of an organization interested in applying a standard change-management process will employ these disciplines as policies and procedures for establishing baselines, manage and control change, and monitor and assess the effectiveness and correctness of progress.
[src:python-dotenv/configuration-management] The IEEE 12207 process IEEE 12207.2 also has these activities and adds "Release management and delivery".
[src:python-dotenv/configuration-management] Configuration Identification (CI): consists of setting and maintaining baselines, which define the system or subsystem architecture, components, and any developments at any point in time.
[src:python-dotenv/configuration-management] It is the basis by which changes to any part of a system are identified, documented, and later tracked through design, development, testing, and final delivery.
[src:python-dotenv/configuration-management] CI incrementally establishes and maintains the definitive current basis for Configuration Status Accounting (CSA) of a system and its configuration items (CIs) throughout their life cycle (development, production, deployment, and operational support) until disposal.
[src:python-dotenv/configuration-management] Configuration Control: includes the evaluation of all change-requests and change-proposals, and their subsequent approval or disapproval.
[src:python-dotenv/configuration-management] It covers the process of controlling modifications to the system's design, hardware, firmware, software, and documentation.
[src:python-dotenv/configuration-management] Configuration Status Accounting: includes the process of recording and reporting configuration item descriptions (e.g., hardware, software, firmware, etc.) and all departures from the baseline during design and production.
[src:python-dotenv/configuration-management] In the event of suspected problems, operators can quickly verify baseline configuration and approved modifications.
[src:python-dotenv/configuration-management] Configuration Verification and Audit: an independent review of hardware and software for the purpose of assessing compliance with established performance requirements, commercial and appropriate military standards, and functional, allocated, and product baselines.
[src:python-dotenv/configuration-management] Configuration audits verify that the system and subsystem configuration documentation complies with the functional and physical performance characteristics before acceptance into an architectural baseline.
[src:python-dotenv/configuration-management] The software configuration management (SCM) process is looked upon by practitioners as the best solution to handling changes in software projects.
[src:python-dotenv/configuration-management] It identifies the functional and physical attributes of software at various points in time, and performs systematic control of changes to the identified attributes for the purpose of maintaining software integrity and traceability throughout the software development life cycle.
[src:python-dotenv/configuration-management] The SCM process further defines the need to trace changes, and the ability to verify that the final delivered software has all of the planned enhancements that are supposed to be included in the release.
[src:python-dotenv/configuration-management] It identifies four procedures that must be defined for each software project to ensure that a sound SCM process is implemented.
[src:python-dotenv/configuration-management] These terms and definitions can change somewhat from standard to standard.
[src:python-dotenv/configuration-management] ITIL specifies the use of a configuration management system (CMS) or configuration management database (CMDB) as a means of achieving industry best practices for Configuration Management.
[src:python-dotenv/configuration-management] CMS helps manage a federated collection of CMDBs.
[src:python-dotenv/configuration-management] The benefits of a CMS/CMDB includes being able to perform functions like root cause analysis, impact analysis, change management, and current state assessment for future state strategy development.
[src:python-dotenv/configuration-management] For information assurance, CM can be defined as the management of security features and assurances through control of changes made to hardware, software, firmware, documentation, test, test fixtures, and test documentation throughout the life cycle of an information system.
[src:python-dotenv/configuration-management] For example, configuration requirements may be different for a network firewall that functions as part of an organization's Internet boundary versus one that functions as an internal local network firewall.
[src:python-dotenv/configuration-management] Configuration management is used to maintain an understanding of the status of complex assets with a view to maintaining the highest level of serviceability for the lowest cost.
[src:python-dotenv/configuration-management] Specifically, it aims to ensure that operations are not disrupted due to the asset (or parts of the asset) overrunning limits of planned lifespan or below quality levels.
[src:python-dotenv/configuration-management] In the military, this type of activity is often classed as "mission readiness", and seeks to define which assets are available and for which type of mission; a classic example is whether aircraft on board an aircraft carrier are equipped with bombs for ground support or missiles for defense.
[src:python-dotenv/configuration-management] Configuration management can be used to maintain OS configuration files.
[src:python-dotenv/configuration-management] Many of these systems utilize Infrastructure as Code to define and maintain configuration.
[src:python-dotenv/configuration-management] The Promise theory of configuration maintenance was developed by Mark Burgess, with a practical implementation on present day computer systems in the software CFEngine able to perform real time repair as well as preventive maintenance.
[src:python-dotenv/configuration-management] Understanding the "as is" state of an asset and its major components is an essential element in preventive maintenance as used in maintenance, repair, and overhaul and enterprise asset management systems.
[src:python-dotenv/configuration-management] Complex assets such as aircraft, ships, industrial machinery etc. depend on many different components being serviceable.
[src:python-dotenv/configuration-management] This serviceability is often defined in terms of the amount of usage the component has had since it was new, since fitted, since repaired, the amount of use it has had over its life and several other limiting factors.
[src:python-dotenv/configuration-management] Understanding how near the end of their life each of these components is has been a major undertaking involving labor-intensive record keeping until recent developments in software.
[src:python-dotenv/configuration-management] Many types of component use electronic sensors to capture data which provides live condition monitoring.
[src:python-dotenv/configuration-management] This data is analyzed on board or at a remote location by computer to evaluate its current serviceability and increasingly its likely future state using algorithms which predict potential future failures based on previous examples of failure through field experience and modeling.
[src:python-dotenv/configuration-management] This is the basis for "predictive maintenance".
[src:python-dotenv/configuration-management] Availability of accurate and timely data is essential in order for CM to provide operational value and a lack of this can often be a limiting factor.
[src:python-dotenv/configuration-management] Capturing and disseminating the operating data to the various support organizations is becoming an industry in itself.
[src:python-dotenv/configuration-management] The consumers of this data have grown more numerous and complex with the growth of programs offered by original equipment manufacturers (OEMs).
[src:python-dotenv/configuration-management] These are designed to offer operators guaranteed availability and make the picture more complex with the operator managing the asset but the OEM taking on the liability to ensure its serviceability.
[src:python-dotenv/configuration-management] More recently configuration management has been applied to large construction projects which can often be very complex and have a huge number of details and changes that need to be documented.
[src:python-dotenv/configuration-management] Construction agencies such as the Federal Highway Administration have used configuration management for their infrastructure projects.
[src:python-dotenv/configuration-management] There are construction-based configuration management tools that aim to document change orders and RFIs in order to ensure a project stays on schedule and on budget.
[src:python-dotenv/configuration-management] These programs can also store information to aid in the maintenance and modification of the infrastructure when it is completed.
[src:python-dotenv/configuration-management] This study yielded results indicating a benefit to using configuration management on projects of this nature.
[src:python-dotenv/environment-variable-p01] An **environment variable** is a user-definable value that can affect the way running processes will behave on a computer.
[src:python-dotenv/environment-variable-p01] Environment variables are part of the environment in which a process runs.
[src:python-dotenv/environment-variable-p01] For example, a running process can query the value of the TEMP environment variable to discover a suitable location to store temporary files, or the HOME or USERPROFILE variable to find the directory structure owned by the user running the process.
[src:python-dotenv/environment-variable-p01] They were introduced in their modern form in 1979 with Version 7 Unix, so are included in all Unix operating system flavors and variants from that point onward including Linux and macOS.
[src:python-dotenv/environment-variable-p01] From PC DOS 2.0 in 1982, all succeeding Microsoft operating systems, including Microsoft Windows, and OS/2 also have included them as a feature, although with somewhat different syntax, usage and standard variable names.
[src:python-dotenv/environment-variable-p01] In all Unix and Unix-like systems, as well as on Windows, each process has its own separate set of environment variables.
[src:python-dotenv/environment-variable-p01] By default, when a process is created, it inherits a duplicate run-time environment of its parent process, except for explicit changes made by the parent when it creates the child.
[src:python-dotenv/environment-variable-p01] At the API level, these changes must be done between running `fork` and `exec`.
[src:python-dotenv/environment-variable-p01] Alternatively, from command shells such as bash, a user can change environment variables for a particular command invocation by indirectly invoking it via `env` or using the `ENVIRONMENT_VARIABLE=VALUE <command>` notation.
[src:python-dotenv/environment-variable-p01] A running program can access the values of environment variables for configuration purposes.
[src:python-dotenv/environment-variable-p01] Shell scripts and batch files use environment variables to communicate data and preferences to child processes.
[src:python-dotenv/environment-variable-p01] They can also be used to store temporary values for reference later in a shell script.
[src:python-dotenv/environment-variable-p01] However, in Unix, non-exported variables are preferred for this as they do not leak outside the process.
[src:python-dotenv/environment-variable-p01] In Unix, an environment variable that is changed in a script or compiled program will only affect that process and possibly child processes.
[src:python-dotenv/environment-variable-p01] The parent process and any unrelated processes will not be affected.
[src:python-dotenv/environment-variable-p01] Similarly, changing or removing a variable's value inside a DOS or Windows batch file will change the variable for the duration of `COMMAND.COM`or `CMD.EXE`'s existence, respectively.
[src:python-dotenv/environment-variable-p01] In Unix, the environment variables are normally initialized during system startup by the system init startup scripts, and hence inherited by all other processes in the system.
[src:python-dotenv/environment-variable-p01] Users can, and often do, augment them in the profile script for the command shell they are using.
[src:python-dotenv/environment-variable-p01] In Microsoft Windows, each environment variable's default value is stored in the Windows Registry or set in the `AUTOEXEC.BAT` file.
[src:python-dotenv/environment-variable-p01] On Unix, a setuid program is given an environment chosen by its caller, but it runs with different authority from its caller.
[src:python-dotenv/environment-variable-p01] The dynamic linker will usually load code from locations specified by the environment variables `$LD_LIBRARY_PATH` and `$LD_PRELOAD` and run it with the process's authority.
[src:python-dotenv/environment-variable-p01] If a setuid program did this, it would be insecure, because its caller could get it to run arbitrary code and hence misuse its authority.
[src:python-dotenv/environment-variable-p01] For this reason, libc unsets these environment variables at startup in a setuid process. setuid programs usually unset unknown environment variables and check others or set them to reasonable values.
[src:python-dotenv/environment-variable-p01] In general, the collection of environment variables function as an associative array where both the keys and values are strings.
[src:python-dotenv/environment-variable-p01] The interpretation of characters in either string differs among systems.
[src:python-dotenv/environment-variable-p01] When data structures such as lists need to be represented, it is common to use a colon (common on Unix and Unix-like) or semicolon-delineated (common on Windows and DOS) list.
[src:python-dotenv/environment-variable-p01] The variables can be used both in scripts and on the command line.
[src:python-dotenv/environment-variable-p01] They are usually referenced by putting special symbols in front of or around the variable name.
[src:python-dotenv/environment-variable-p01] By convention, names of environment variables are normally expressed in all capital letters.
[src:python-dotenv/environment-variable-p01] This helps keep environment variables distinctly different from other variables and identifiers used in programming codes.
[src:python-dotenv/environment-variable-p01] Nevertheless, note that case sensitivity in environment variable names differs between operating systems.
[src:python-dotenv/environment-variable-p01] That is, Unix-like operating systems are case-sensitive with respect to environment variable names, while DOS, OS/2, and Windows are not case-sensitive.
[src:python-dotenv/environment-variable-p01] In most Unix and Unix-like command-line shells, an environment variable's value is retrieved by placing a `$` sign before the variable's name.
[src:python-dotenv/environment-variable-p01] If necessary, the name can also be surrounded by braces.
[src:python-dotenv/environment-variable-p01] In Unix and Unix-like systems, the names of environment variables are case-sensitive.
[src:python-dotenv/environment-variable-p01] The command **`env`** displays all environment variables and their values.
[src:python-dotenv/environment-variable-p01] The command **`printenv`** can also be used to print a single variable by giving that variable name as the sole argument to the command.
[src:python-dotenv/environment-variable-p01] In DOS, OS/2 and Windows command-line interpreters such as `COMMAND.COM` and `CMD.EXE`, an environment variable is retrieved by placing a `%` sign before and after it.
[src:python-dotenv/environment-variable-p01] In DOS, OS/2 and Windows command-line interpreters as well as their API, upper or lower case is not distinguished for environment variable names.
[src:python-dotenv/environment-variable-p01] The environment variable named `HOMEDRIVE` contains the drive letter (plus its trailing `:` colon) of the user's home directory, whilst `HOMEPATH` contains the full path of the user's home directory within that drive.
[src:python-dotenv/environment-variable-p01] The command **`SET`** (with no arguments) displays all environment variables and their values.
[src:python-dotenv/environment-variable-p01] In Windows NT and later `set` can also be used to print all variables whose name begins with a given prefix by giving the prefix as the sole argument to the command.
[src:python-dotenv/environment-variable-p01] In PowerShell, upper or lower case is not distinguished for environment variable names.
[src:python-dotenv/environment-variable-p01] The commands `env` and `set` can be used to set environment variables and are often incorporated directly into the shell.
[src:python-dotenv/environment-variable-p01] The following commands can also be used, but are often dependent on a certain shell.
[src:python-dotenv/environment-variable-p01] A few simple principles govern how environment variables achieve their effect.
[src:python-dotenv/environment-variable-p01] Environment variables are local to the process in which they were set.
[src:python-dotenv/environment-variable-p01] If two shell processes are spawned and the value of an environment variable is changed in one, that change will not be seen by the other.
[src:python-dotenv/environment-variable-p01] When a child process is created, it inherits all the environment variables and their values from the parent process.
[src:python-dotenv/environment-variable-p01] Usually, when a program calls another program, it first creates a child process by forking, then the child adjusts the environment as needed and lastly the child replaces itself with the program to be called.
[src:python-dotenv/environment-variable-p01] This procedure gives the calling program control over the environment of the called program.
[src:python-dotenv/environment-variable-p01] In Unix shells, variables may be assigned without the **`export`** keyword.
[src:python-dotenv/environment-variable-p01] Variables defined in this way are displayed by the **`set`** command, but are *not* true environment variables, as they are stored only by the shell and are unknown to all other processes.
[src:python-dotenv/environment-variable-p01] The `printenv` command will not display them, and child processes do not inherit them.
[src:python-dotenv/environment-variable-p01] The persistence of an environment variable can be session-wide or system-wide.
[src:python-dotenv/environment-variable-p01] The **`SET`** command without any arguments displays all environment variables along with their values; **`SET " "`**, zero or more spaces, will include internal variables too.
[src:python-dotenv/environment-variable-p01] In `CMD.EXE`, it is possible to assign local variables that will not be global using the **`SETLOCAL`** command and **`ENDLOCAL`** to restore the environment.
[src:python-dotenv/environment-variable-p01] In PHP the `putenv()` function should be used.
[src:python-dotenv/environment-variable-p01] Contains a colon-separated list of directories that the shell searches for commands that do not contain a slash in their name (commands with slashes are interpreted as file names to execute, and the shell attempts to execute the files directly).
[src:python-dotenv/environment-variable-p01] is often used for convenience in various shell scripts (and other contexts).
[src:python-dotenv/environment-variable-p01] Using the environment variable also gives the user the possibility to point to another directory.
[src:python-dotenv/environment-variable-p01] This variable points to the current directory.
[src:python-dotenv/environment-variable-p01] Equivalent to the output of the command pwd when called without arguments.
[src:python-dotenv/environment-variable-p01] , before searching in any other directories.
[src:python-dotenv/environment-variable-p01] , then the language is set to (Brazilian) Portuguese and Brazilian practice is used where relevant.
[src:python-dotenv/environment-variable-p01] can be used to force the same locale for all aspects.
[src:python-dotenv/environment-variable-p01] The browsers in the list are intended to be attempted from first to last, stopping after the first one that succeeds.
[src:python-dotenv/environment-variable-p01] token may be present to specify where the URL should be placed; otherwise the browser should be launched with the URL as the first argument.
[src:python-dotenv/environment-variable-p01] Under DOS, the *master environment* is provided by the primary command processor, which inherits the *pre-environment* defined in `CONFIG.SYS` when first loaded.
[src:python-dotenv/environment-variable-p01] Its size can be configured through the `COMMAND /E:n` parameter between 160 and 32767 bytes.
[src:python-dotenv/environment-variable-p01] *Local environment* segments inherited to child processes are typically reduced down to the size of the contents they hold.
[src:python-dotenv/environment-variable-p01] Some command-line processors (like 4DOS) allow to define a minimum amount of free environment space that will be available when launching secondary shells.
[src:python-dotenv/environment-variable-p01] In principle, MS-DOS 7.0 and higher also supports lowercase variable names (`%windir%`), but provides no means for the user to define them.
[src:python-dotenv/environment-variable-p01] Environment variable names containing lowercase letters are stored in the environment just like normal environment variables, but remain invisible to most DOS software, since they are written to expect uppercase variables only.
[src:python-dotenv/environment-variable-p01] Some command processors limit the maximum length of a variable name to 80 characters.
[src:python-dotenv/environment-variable-p01] While principally only limited by the size of the *environment segment*, some DOS and 16-bit Windows programs do not expect the contents of environment variables to exceed 128 characters.
[src:python-dotenv/environment-variable-p01] DR-DOS `COMMAND.COM` supports environment variables up to 255, 4DOS even up to 512 characters.
[src:python-dotenv/environment-variable-p01] Since `COMMAND.COM` can be configured (via `/L:128..1024`) to support command lines up to 1024 characters internally under MS-DOS 7.0 and higher, environment variables should be expected to contain at least 1024 characters as well.
